  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Despite its 2020 publication, \"Strategic Imaginations\" has yet to garner citations or online discussions across major platforms, limiting its immediate visibility and impact within the academic and public spheres.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">\"Strategic Imaginations,\" published by Leuven University Press in 2020, explores themes pertinent to strategic thought and imaginative frameworks within various contexts. However, to date, the book has not achieved any citations according to the OpenAlex database, indicating a limited academic footprint since its release.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The absence of online mentions on significant platforms such as Wikipedia, Reddit, and Bluesky suggests that there has been little societal or public engagement with the work. This lack of community discourse can impact the book's reach and relevance, as discussions in public forums often amplify academic publications and cultivate broader interest.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The book's trajectory demonstrates a reliance on traditional academic pathways for its recognition. While commercial linkages are identified\u2014strongly associated with platforms like Amazon and Goodreads\u2014these connections do not compensate for the lack of academic discourse or citation by scholars actively engaging with its themes.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The framework of \"Strategic Imaginations\" may still hold potential for future engagement within academic circles, particularly as scholars explore new dimensions of strategic methodologies. Nevertheless, as of now, it remains to be seen how this work may integrate into ongoing dialogues in its relevant fields.</p>",
